metadata.title: Cessna 150
aws::graph::propositions: Cessna 150 Aircraft Model Variations
The original metal wingtips on the Cessna 150 were replaced by more smoothly contoured fiberglass ones.
The fiberglass wingtips had a different shape than the metal wingtips.
The fiberglass wingtips increased the wingspan by about 2 inches (50 mm).
The Cessna 150 had an optional two-passenger child seat for the baggage compartment.
The optional two-passenger child seat was available from the first Cessna 150.
The optional two-passenger child seat was completely redesigned for the Cessna 150B.
The Cessna 150B had a new option called "Nav-O-Matic".
"Nav-O-Matic" was a simple autopilot.
"Nav-O-Matic" was specifically for the Commuter version of the Cessna 150B.
"Nav-O-Matic" was a single-axis heading-hold type autopilot.
The Cessna 150B offered optional "courtesy lights" in the underside of the wings.
The "courtesy lights" illuminated the area around the doors when on the ground.
The Patroller message drop tube option was eliminated for the Cessna 150B.
350 Cessna 150B aircraft were built.
The Cessna 150C was the 1963 model year.
The Cessna 150C added a quick drain to the fuel strainer.
The Cessna 150C offered optional larger 6.00×6 inch (150×150 mm) main wheels and tires.
The standard wheel and tire size for the Cessna 150C was 5.00×5 inch (125×125 mm).
The Cessna 150C had an optional child seat.

text:
The original metal wingtips were replaced by more smoothly contoured fiberglass ones with a different shape, increasing the wingspan by about 2 inches (50 mm).  The optional two-passenger child seat for the baggage compartment, available from the first 150, was completely redesigned for the 150B.  A new option was a simple autopilot, specifically for the Commuter version, called "Nav-O-Matic", a single-axis heading-hold type. Also newly offered for the 150B were optional "courtesy lights" in the underside of the wings to light the area around the doors when on the ground.  The Patroller message drop tube option, on the other hand, was eliminated.  350 built.
150C
1963 model year with a quick drain added to the fuel strainer, optional larger 6.00×6 inch (150×150 mm) main wheels and tires to replace the standard 5.00×5 inch (125×125 mm) size, and an optional child seat.
